specialcase.p:
Consider the standard basis of \R^3 from this :
e_1=\vec{1 0 0},\quad e_2=\vec{0 1 0}, \quad e_3=\vec{0 0 1}.
According to the above , every vector in \R^3 can be written as a linear combination of e_1,e_2,e_3, with unique coefficients.  For example,
v = \vec{\color{seq1}3 \color{seq2}5 \color{seq3}{-2}}
= \textcolor{seq1}{3}\vec{1 0 0} + \textcolor{seq2}{5}\vec{0 1 0}
\textcolor{seq3}{{}- 2}\vec{0 0 1}
= \textcolor{seq1}{3}e_1 + \textcolor{seq2}{5}e_2
\textcolor{seq3}{{}- 2}e_3.
In this case, the coordinates of v are exactly the coefficients of e_1,e_2,e_3.

solution.p:



            By the , any two linearly independent vectors form a basis for \R^2.  Clearly v_1,v_2 are not multiples of each other, so they are linearly independent.



            To say [w]_\cB={1\choose 2} means that 1 is the v_1-coordinate of w, and that 2 is the v_2-coordinate:
            w = v_1 + 2v_2 = \vec{1 1} + 2\vec{1 -1} = \vec{3 -1}.



            We have to solve the vector equation v=c_1v_1 + c_2v_2 in the unknowns c_1,c_2.  We form an augmented matrix and row reduce:
            \amat{1 1 5; 1 -1 3}
            \quad\xrightarrow{\text{RREF}}\quad
            \amat{1 0 4; 0 1 1}.
            We have c_1=4 and c_2=1, so v = 4v_1+v_2 and
            [v]_\cB = {4\choose1}.


        In the following picture, we indicate the coordinate system defined by \cB by drawing lines parallel to the v_1-axis and v_2-axis.  Using this grid it is easy to see that the \cB-coordinates of v are {5\choose 1}, and that the \cB-coordinates of w are {1\choose 2}.

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.7, thin border nodes]

  \draw (-6, -6) rectangle (6, 6);
  \clip (-6, -6) rectangle (6, 6);

  \draw[scale={sqrt(2)}, rotate=45, help lines] (-7, -7) grid (7, 7);
  \draw[vector, seq-blue] (0, 0) to["$v_1$" above left] (1, 1);
  \draw[vector, seq-green] (0, 0) to["$v_2$" below left] (1, -1);

  \point[seq-red, "$w$" {above,text=seq-red}] at (3, -1);
  \point[seq-orange, "$v$" {above,text=seq-orange}] at (5, 3);

  \point at (0, 0);

\end{tikzpicture}

        This picture could be the grid of streets in Palo Alto, California.  Residents of Palo Alto refer to northwest as north and to northeast as east.  There is a reason for this: the old road to San Francisco is called El Camino Real, and that road runs from the southeast to the northwest in Palo Alto.  So when a Palo Alto resident says go south two blocks and east one block, they are giving directions from the origin to the Whole Foods at w.

specialcase.p:
    Let
    v_1 = \vec[r]{2 -1 1} \quad v_2 = \vec[r]{1 0 -1}.
    These form a basis \cB for a plane V = \Span\{v_1,v_2\} in \R^3.  We indicate the coordinate system defined by \cB by drawing lines parallel to the v_1-axis and v_2-axis:

\begin{tikzpicture}[myxyz, z={(0cm,1.2cm)}, thin border nodes]
  \useasboundingbox[resetxy] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,2.3);

  \def\v{(2,-1,1)}
  \def\w{(1,0,-1)}

  \node[coordinate] (X) at \v {};
  \node[coordinate] (Y) at \w {};

  \begin{scope}[x=(X), y=(Y), transformxy]
    \fill[seq4!10, nearly opaque] (-1,-1) rectangle (1,1);
    \draw[step=.5cm, seq4!80, thin] (-1,-1) grid (1,1);
  \end{scope}

  \begin{scope}[x=($.5*(X)$), y=($.5*(Y)$), every label/.append style={fill=none}]
    \point[minimum size=1.5mm, seq1, "$u_1$" {seq1, xshift=-2mm}] at (1,1);
    \point[minimum size=1.5mm, seq2, "$u_2$" {seq2, right}] at (-1,.5);
    \point[minimum size=1.5mm, seq3, "$u_3$" seq3] at (1.5,-.5);
    \point[minimum size=1.5mm, seq5, "$u_4$" {seq5, right}] at (0,1.5);
  \end{scope}

  \draw[vector] (0,0,0) to["$v_1$"'] ($.5*(X)$);
  \draw[vector] (0,0,0) to["$v_2$"] ($.5*(Y)$);

  \node[x=(X),y=(Y),seq-violet] at (0,-1.2) {$V$};

  \point at (0,0,0);
\end{tikzpicture}

    We can see from the picture that the v_1-coordinate of \color{seq-red}u_1 is equal to 1, as is the v_2-coordinate, so
    [\textcolor{seq1}{u_1}]_\cB = {1\choose 1}.
    Similarly, we have

      [\textcolor{seq2}{u_2}]_\cB
      = \vec[r]{-1 \frac 12}\qquad
      [\textcolor{seq3}{u_3}]_\cB
      = \vec[r]{\frac 32 -\frac 12}\qquad
      [\textcolor{seq5}{u_4}]_\cB
      = \vec{0 \frac 32}.
